    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Relations: Friends and Allies Across The Divide.; Dave Renwick and Vijay Singh</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Peter de Jonge</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">De Jonge, Peter</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Golfer Vijay Singh, Fiji-born golfer of Indian descent, and Dave Renwick, his white caddy, discuss their friendship across racial divide; photo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Singh: I was born in Fiji, of Indian descent. No doubt, I'm black.</p>
        <p>Renwick: Vijay would certainly get a lot more media hype if he were white.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Singh: I was born in Fiji, of Indian descent. No doubt, I'm black.</p>
        <p>Renwick: Vijay would certainly get a lot more media hype if he were white.</p>
        <p>Singh: I think it has more to do with me being a foreigner. I get asked about race all the time, but I stay away from it. As soon as you talk about it, the tension builds, and it's hard enough already to concentrate on what you're doing.</p>
        <p>Renwick: The idea of a white man caddying for a black golfer might have seemed strange once, but now there are hardly any black caddies out here at all -- five or six at most. You'd have to go back to the 70's, when the prize money was a fraction of what it is now, to find a majority of the caddies who were black. But our relationship is professional, not personal. Race doesn't really come into it.</p>
        <p>Singh: After the round, caddies go one way. Players go another.</p>
        <p>Renwick: We already spend enough time with each other as it is.</p>
      </block>
